[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Comment Quality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Comments are strong throughout:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* PuLP is chosen (clean modeling API, solver-agnostic, CBC ships free)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* the optimizer doesn't talk to the EHR directly (separation of concerns, ETL pipeline)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* weights encode value judgments (no mathematically "correct" answer)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* the one-service-per-block constraint uses `<=` not `==` (blocks can be unassigned)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* the disruption penalty exists (human acceptance of schedule changes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Explain *why* the fairness bonus targets underserved services specifically
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The Gap to Production section is exceptionally thorough, covering solver choice, error handling, input validation, linearization, scenario management, containerization, logging, IAM, VPC, and testing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The sample input data section with the "demand equals supply" note helps readers understand why this is a tight optimization problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
